title: For Sale/Trade:  KELTEC KSG 12 GAUGE BRAND NEW
postcontent: Brand new Keltec KSG 12 gaugePlease feel free to stop in or contact us anytime. We also take trades.The KSG (Kel-Tec Shotgun) is Kel-Tec CNC’s first entry into the shotgun market. The size, shape, and design is similar to the currently available Kel-Tec RFB rifle, but the KSG ejects downward, instead of forward. The KSG weighs 6.9 lbs. and is as compact as legally possible with a 26.1” overall length and an 18.5” cylinder bore barrel. Even with this compact size, the internal dual tube magazines hold an impressive 12 rounds of 12 gauge 3” rounds in total (6 per tube). It can also reliably shoot shells as short as 1 3/4" up to the 3".This simple and reliable pump action feeds from either the left or right tube. The feed side is manually selected by a lever located behind the trigger guard. The pump includes an under picatinny rail for the mounting of a forward grip, a light, or a laser. The included top picatinny sight rail will accept many types of optics or iron sights. Forward and rear sling loops are built in, and a basic sling is included. The soft rubber butt pad helps to tame recoil. The KSG receiver is made from hardened steel and includes the magazine tubes which have been welded in place. The grip and stock assembly is made of glass reinforced nylon (Zytel) and is easily disassembled by pushing out 2 pins, which store in 2 holes in the grip when removed. The barrel and pump assembly is removed by loosening the 2 front magazine tube nuts with a coin and sliding the assembly forward.

postcontent: The M3 Convertible is a no-nonsense shotgun that military and police all over the world depend on. This shotgun can be quickly changed from a fast cycling semi-auto for conventional loads to a manual pump action for low energy special purpose loads such as gas, beanbag and rubber bullet loads. For semi-auto action, merely rotate the selector ring 1/4 turn, push the forend forward and release the selector, to switch back to pump action simply reverse the procedure by pulling back after the selector ring is rotated to lock the forend to the action bars. (Option two) To change between semi-auto and pump action simply rotate the selector ring at the front of the forend 1/4 turn then push forward to change from pump action to semi-auto or pull back to switch from semi-auto to pump action and then release the selector. The M3 Convertible comes in Army Green synthetic stocks, fully adjustable ghost-ring aperture rear sights and military style fixed-blade front sights. title: For Sale:  K98 German Mauser 1942 Sauer & Sohn
postcontent:
Nice early 1942 CE, J.P. Sauer und Sohn, WWII production K98k in a laminated stock with a visible "H" Heer (German Army) mark. Numbers don't match.  However, the barrel is original to the receiver, based on the registration mark and correct WaAs for a 1942 Sauer (see “Backbone of the Wehrmacht”, p. 188). Good bluing below the woodline. Some eagles are lightly scrubbed. Counter-bored. Dark bore with fairly deep rifling but rounded. Judge for yourself from the pictures. No shellac, no crossed rifles, not a Russian Capture. Look at the pictures and please ask questions. 

The decision to fire a used firearm is solely the responsibility of the buyer and this decision is best made with the input of a professional gunsmith.

I know a trusted FFL in my area that I can work with for the transfer ($25), or I will use an FFL-01 or equivalent of your choosing.  Buyer pays the FFL transfer fee.  Those who don't believe they can pass a NICS check when answering honestly should not even contact me.   

I am willing to ship inside WA or outside of WA to the proper type of FFL.  This item is in original military configuration and is C&R (FFL-03) eligible.  I am an FFL-03 holder.  For face to face purchase I prefer cash or a USPS MO.  For shipping I require a USPS MO.  You can check my feedback on GunBroker, username: milsurp762

This item is cross-listed on GB, so a BIN on GB (automatic contract), followed by full price offers on Armslist, followed by highest offer, followed by time stamp of tied "I will purchase" highest offers will be used to determine who wins the rifle. This determination will be made solely by the seller (me).  I will do so honestly and fairly as described above.

Thanks for looking!

title: For Sale:  Star Model B
postcontent:
A fun little piece of history! It looks like a 1911, but it's chambered in 9mm. It was produced by the Spanish in WWII based on the stolen U.S. designs. The Nazi's took possession of the Stars for their home guard. Even though these are definitely used, they probably weren't pointed at U.S. soldiers. Finally, the Russian Army confiscated the pistols from the Nazis. That's when they sold it back to the US for resale. Quite the tale!

This particular example was made in 1945. That's really all I can tell from the proof marks.

This is example is from 1945 as far as I can tell from the proof marks. I have two 8-round mags. I've only shot 40 or 50 rounds through it, though it definitely saw lots of use long before it came to me.
